<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/63640052-spencer-miller"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1512413712i/63640052._UX100_CR0,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/63640052-spencer-miller">Spencer Miller</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">3/10 It can spark some interesting discussion, but in my opinion, there are much better books for young readers to spend their time with. This book de<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">3/10 It can spark some interesting discussion, but in my opinion, there are much better books for young readers to spend their time with. This book deals with themes such as corruption, violence, and hopelessness. Though interesting topics in and of themselves, probably not the most vital or interesting topics to a classroom of middle schoolers. I would consider something less depressing that your students might actually get excited about reading. <a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
