              <span id="reviewTextContainer3701008730" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16915338970655060322">* “Do I Dare Disturb the Universe?” - Jerry Renault, The Chocolate War. <br/><br/>I remember the feeling of shock I had when I finished The Chocolate War for the first time. I sat in utter disbelief. I even re-read the last 20 pages again to make sure I read the book correctly. Never had a book impacted me as an aspiring author like the book I had just put down. <br/><br/>The Chocolate War is set-up like many young adult books in the genre. The main protagonist is reeling from the tragic and sudden loss of his moth</span>
  <span id="freeText16915338970655060322" style="display:none">* “Do I Dare Disturb the Universe?” - Jerry Renault, The Chocolate War. <br /><br />I remember the feeling of shock I had when I finished The Chocolate War for the first time. I sat in utter disbelief. I even re-read the last 20 pages again to make sure I read the book correctly. Never had a book impacted me as an aspiring author like the book I had just put down. <br /><br />The Chocolate War is set-up like many young adult books in the genre. The main protagonist is reeling from the tragic and sudden loss of his mother before going to a new (all-boys) high school. It hits many of the tenets in “coming of age” works. Jerry copes with loss, he works to find himself, and stands up against an unjust system and rallies his peers against the system. This set-up is comfortably familiar, but the direction the story goes impacted me in such a way that I was left reeling for weeks. The book explores and meditates on tenets of existentialism, conformity, and institutions of power — all through a.. school chocolate sale. That doesn’t diminish the impact of the novel’s explorations, but rather, makes you feel the weight of Jerry’s experiences through his own eyes<br /><br />An underground student society that has a decades long tradition at Trinity, led by a student named Archie Costello. This student society enforces order at the school, and, while “banned”, the school administrators look the other way as long as the “order” Is maintained. Jerry Renault, the protagonist of the novel, throws a wrench into the order of the entire school when he says “no.” to the Chocolate sales. Jerry accidentally becomes the flashpoint for starting an entire movement at Trinity to refuse to sell chocolate. Creating a ripple effect that has unintended consequences all the way up the ladder at Trinity.<br /><br />Under the pressure against the administrators of the school, the elite students at Trinity in the vigils, and trying to find the meaning to his life after the passing of his mother, Jerry asks himself “Do I dare disturb the universe?” a question asked about his simple protest to a chocolate sale. But the book works so much as an allegory for the difficulty and reaction to when we work to protest injustice, start social movements, and even work to change the basic habits we’ve developed to conform to societal expectations. The book is boosted by fantastic characters, with Archie continuing to be one of my favorite antagonists I’ve ever read. The brutality that our world has to those who “disturb the universe” is shown in great detail here, and causes this book to be a page turner at the very end. <br /><br />Robert Cormier’s works throughout his life as well as his novels endings were a lighting rod of controversy. The Chocolate War was no exception, being the 3rd highest banned book in the country from 2000-2009. His works I am the Cheese, Fade, After the First Death, and We All Fall Down also routinely appeared on ban lists. I am so thankful to have found Robert Cormier and The Chocolate War as its ending continues to hang with me. it was in those breathless moments after finishing that work that I knew that the books I wanted to write about bullying could be written, (even if it only got read by myself and my Mom), and I was left wanting to "disturb the universe"</span>
  <a data-text-id="16915338970655060322" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

