  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_39822765" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/39822765" />
    <a title="Kandice" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1396160-kandice"><img alt="Kandice" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1231810788p2/1396160.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/39822765?book_show_action=true">Dec 10, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kandice" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kandice" href="/user/show/1396160-kandice">Kandice</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer39822765" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4001178320483895957">Trinity is an all boy Catholic school. As part of an annual Trinity fundraiser Brother Leon has pledged the boys to sell 20,000 boxes of chocolate, up 100% from the normal 10,000 boxes goal. Not only that, the chocolates cost $2 instead of the usual $1. <br/><br/>Trinity is ruled by an elite clique, The Vigils, and the person who runs that clique is Archie Costello. Archie creates “assignments” for his fellow students: various stunts and pranks.<br/><br/>Jerry is a Trinity freshman. Archie’s assignment to Jerry is </span>
  <span id="freeText4001178320483895957" style="display:none">Trinity is an all boy Catholic school. As part of an annual Trinity fundraiser Brother Leon has pledged the boys to sell 20,000 boxes of chocolate, up 100% from the normal 10,000 boxes goal. Not only that, the chocolates cost $2 instead of the usual $1. <br /><br />Trinity is ruled by an elite clique, The Vigils, and the person who runs that clique is Archie Costello. Archie creates “assignments” for his fellow students: various stunts and pranks.<br /><br />Jerry is a Trinity freshman. Archie’s assignment to Jerry is simple: say “no” to selling chocolate for two weeks, then say “yes.” That’s it, but Jerry never says yes. At the same time Archie’s telling Jerry not to sell chocolates, he’s told Brother Leon that he’s going to get The Vigils to make this the best chocolate sale ever. His fellow Vigils aren’t too thrilled with Archie because this is a hard order to fill and The Vigils don’t fail.<br /><br />Jerry is supposed to be the main character. It’s his refusal to sell chocolate that begins and propels the plot, and we are even given a look at Jerry’s life outside of school: a dead mother, a busy father, a girl he may like. And yet, when it comes to one of the most critical points in the book — Jerry being assigned to say “no” and saying “no” — Jerry is absent. His viewpoint isn’t shared. We don’t get his view again until he decides to say “no” after Archie tells him to say “yes.”<br /><br />For me, Archie seems to be the main character. He is the puppet master, and even though we learn nothing personal about him, i.e. parents, siblings, social status, everything that happens can, in some way, everything that happens can be traced back to Archie. I like how clearly his character is drawn. He is a manipulator; he is the smartest person in the room; he totally lacks empathy. He’s either going to be a fantastic success or a serial killer.<br /><br />Trinity boys do what Archie tells them to do, always, so how does Jerry resist? I can see Archie leading Jerry to a place of “no.” And this is what I loved about The Chocolate War: because of the different, even unreliable voices telling the story, we can’t really know what each character thought, meant, intended, or even believed in. We are given a few details of Jerry’s life to lull us into believing that not selling the chocolate is a protest on jerry’s part. I think he decides not to sell the chocolates, even when finally told to do so, is because Archie has led him to that decision.<br /><br />The book ends with an incredibly violent and visceral scene. One which made my stomach turn to read. By making Archie a sociopath without remorse, the reader, who is shocked by the end, who is feeling empathy, can say to themselves, I’m better than Archie because I wouldn’t go that far. I would feel terrible. That’s the real genius of this book. Not being told what the characters do, but allowing us to tell ourselves what we would not. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="4001178320483895957" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


